    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Many Lessons of Whitewater</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Edwin D Condon letter says one lesson of Whitewater case is that Congress should not hamper executive branch by unrelenting, politically inspired, investigations</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your ''lessons to be learned'' from the independent counsel's Whitewater report (editorial, Sept. 21), you did not mention one powerful lesson: that Congress should not hamper the executive branch by unrelenting investigations that often appear to be politically driven. The Clinton presidency has been dogged by an overzealous Congress in this area.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your ''lessons to be learned'' from the independent counsel's Whitewater report (editorial, Sept. 21), you did not mention one powerful lesson: that Congress should not hamper the executive branch by unrelenting investigations that often appear to be politically driven. The Clinton presidency has been dogged by an overzealous Congress in this area.</p>
        <p>Congress has made itself a collection of sheriffs who find it easier to pursue investigations and special counsels than enter into the give-and-take of the legislative process.</p>
        <p>Perhaps the general election may help to focus more sharply on the real job description of the legislative branch.</p>
        <p>EDWIN D. CONDON  Westwood, Mass., Sept. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
